Comment: This movie was very..... Alright. A lot of people were complaining about the jaegers feeling weightless and too fast but that wasn't a problem. This takes place years after the first movie and the technology was much more advanced, making them way faster. That being said the jaeger vs kaiju scenes were pretty great and the jaeger vs jaeger parts were almost perfect. The story itself was pretty solid thanks to Del Torro and for the most part the action was awesome. The designs for the monsters and jaegers I think were more original in the first movie. My biggest issue was with the kids they put in main roles. I didn't like a single one and at times it was downright annoying watching them and the sript was absolute garbage. They just took away from the seriousness of many scenes. Fin and discount Paul Walker did alright but I would prefer more of the original cast to return in the third movie if it happens. Id still go see it. I really hope Del Torro is in the directors seat.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment: I went to the cinema yesterday to see this, and was pretty much going in with negative mood, from the comments I read on the youtube and heard from people. I never again watch and read comments and trailers anymore. I loved the movie, it exactly got what I loved. The action, stunts, plot twists and to be honest, I kinda like this sequel. Also, I didnt find any annoying character here as in some movies there are. The blue light and feel of the base where Jags were was cool! What is more, I thought that I would really be upset to see super kids saving the day, but to be honest, the Amara was not annoying kid, she was genuinely likeable character. I liked the characters even though they didnt have enough developement, maybe Im shallow. I really wish this would got a good box office and we would see trilogy. Please, dont get distracted by bad comments here. If you liked the first you will like this too. Also, about the fast moving Jaegers, they felt heavy and big. I loved that they were more agile. Not all Jaegers were doing the flips. At last, do you know why I loved Pacific Rim? I have never seen anyone say this but, the thought of humans joining together, and creating bigger robot, which have looks like us, which just reflect our creativity, logic, nature and physic understanding. That our physic weakness goes away. Im not sure if I said this good but here are mine words. Thanks for reading and have a great day!

Comment:
Why are they suddenly children pilots? or atleast very young individuals, the first film it felt like it was a godzilla type of thing, bleak, horrible existance, death and destruction where only godzilla could save humanity, much like the first film where mistakes could not happen because people die, ripped apart, killed off, severe consequences ... this one feels like its going to be a power rangers remake, all colourful, made for kids you know what i mean? like "with the power of love, we can defeat them!" *facepalm

you know what i mean though? its like i went from watching something dark and sinister, to watching yet another transformers film, even the jaegers, they moved rather realistically like they had real weight to them, now they are jumping around and being tossed about like physics suddenly no longer applies to them - i bet you no kids die in this film, i bet they all survive and they all live happily ever after.

Theres nothing wrong with that, it just makes the film feel like im no longer watching pacific rim, the darkness and sinister approach, looks lost ... power rangers feat transformers, kids will love it but i personally am no longer interested if thats their aim.

Another comparison is Marvel and DC, DC is the first film, Marvel took over for the second, again, im not saying thats bad, just that i would have preferred it if DC also did the second :/ lol

Comment:
You have a director that has never done a big budget movie before (and a writer for the Transformers cinematic universe) and John Boyega (first time producer) stupidly wanting faster jagers. At the end of Pacific Rim the Kaiju were already moving pretty fast and the Jagers were keeping up. How fast would these new Kaiju be now to merit stupidly faster Jagers? It breaks the immersion of a giant fight. Just take out all the buildings and all you see are robots fighting aliens not some grand battle against giant beasts. 

And you also have the studio thing of let's have pre teen pilots to appeal to kids. And let's have more of everything (Jagers and Kaiju) so we can milk the toy market. That is literally what Transformers is and this is what Pacific Rim has become of it and you can see it in the trailers. If you can't see that the you are in denial and I hope you have some humility and admit when you see how shit this in the theater.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
To those here who are saying "Oh my god this is just transformers but bigger, it's gonna be shit" or "looks like power rangers and shit. Gonna be a terrible movie", stop and think for a moment. Lore wise, it makes perfect sense that the jeagers would evolve to become much more agile and maneuverable. Most of the jeagers in the first movie aside from Gipsy after being repaired and Striker were clunky and slow. Jeagers were destroyed because most of the time, the kaiju were much faster (i.e. Otachi blitzing Gipsy and Crimson).

Now look at this from an inspiration point of view. I can guarantee that these jeagers are inspired by Evas, Gundams, and Jet Jagur from Godzilla. This and the first one arent movies made to be some adaptation of an American cartoon. Pacific rim is supposed to be an American interpretation of the kaiju/mecha anime genre. Just look at how the jeagers move. They aren't moving like humans like a transformer and it's not cheesy and glamorized like a megazord. It's fluid but still robot like. You can tell they are being controlled and that they are still machines. 

Bottom line, comparisons with transformers and shit shouldn't be made because they are nothing alike

Comment:
While I did think the chunky movements of the Jaegers in the original looked awesome, I don't really think this is that unrealistic to think about. After all, during the Kaiju War, they were under pressure to constantly develop better Jaegers. And we all know how well most people work under pressure. The movie was released in 2013, so it can only be assumed that the first Kaiju attacks happened in 2013. 14 months later, in 2015, they deployed the first Mark-1 Jaeger. TWO YEARS LATER, in July 2017, they deployed the Gypsy Danger, a Mark-3, which is shown to be notably more agile than the Cherno Alpha (Mark-1). And in 2019, they launched the Mark-5 Jaegers (of which we only know about Striker Eureka), which was a lot more agile than Gypsy Danger was, both before and after the Mark-3 Reactivation Program. Considering how much the technology advanced under pressure, where nobody had the time to sit down, relax and think things through properly, I'm not really surprised that the Jaegers in Uprising are in a whole different league than the ones in the original. And besides, they've had several years to develop new Jaegers, in case the Kaiju were to return, and it's not unrealistic to assume that the different countries would constantly try to do something better than the rest. I'm not sure I understand why there's a need for a Jaeger with a Morph Ball mode though, but I suppose there's only one way to find out. And that is by watching the sequel when it comes out.

And yes, I literally just re-watched the first movie. For the third time. I freaking LOVE that movie! I'm going to watch Uprising when it comes out, and I'm probably going to enjoy it like a child, since I'm a huge fan of the Mecha-genre.



Also, it's never been stated that the Jaegers are supposed to be Real Robot-type Mecha...

Majority of Star Wars Films‚Äô Writers & Directors Are White Men

07 Feb, 2018

A new report reveals that in 41 years of the Star Wars franchise, 96 percent of writers and directors hired by Lucasfilm for the movies are white men. George Lucas introduced the world to a galaxy far, far away in 1977 with Star Wars: A New Hope, a space opera he wrote and directed. The stories of Luke Skywalker (Mark Hamill), Leia Organa (Carrie Fisher), and Han Solo (Harrison Ford) captured the attention of moviegoers around the world and inspired a legion of dedicated fans spanning multiple generations. Though it seemed the franchise had concluded with the final installment of Lucas‚Äô prequel trilogy, Disney acquired Lucasfilm in 2012 and announced a revival of the Star Wars film series.

The episodic storyline was relaunched with J.J. Abrams‚Äô Star Wars: The Force Awakens in 2015, but Disney and Lucasfilm also put standalone anthology movies into development, the first of which was Gareth Edwards‚Äô Rogue One: A Star Wars Story in 2016. Rian Johnson‚Äôs Star Wars: The Last Jedi is the latest entry of the franchise to hit theaters, but there are plenty more coming, including Ron Howard‚Äôs Solo: A Star Wars Story, Johnson‚Äôs new trilogy, and the recently announced series of films from Game of Thrones creators David Benioff and D.B. Weiss. However, as Lucasfilm puts more and more movies into development, fans have wondered when the studio will hire a man of color, woman of color, or white woman to helm or direct a Star Wars movie.

Variety‚Äôs Maureen Ryan crunched the numbers in terms of gender and racial representation in major creative roles on the past and confirmed upcoming Star Wars movies. For 17 total films ‚Äì including the original, prequel, and current trilogies, confirmed anthologies, Johnson‚Äôs trilogy, and the new series from Benioff and Weiss (which Ryan estimates will include three films, though Lucasfilm did not announce the exact number of movies they‚Äôll produce) ‚Äì Lucasfilm hired a total of 24 people in roles as writers or directors. Of those 24 people, all but one were white men; the exception is Leigh Brackett, who received a screenplay credit on 1980‚Äôs The Empire Strikes Back. Ryan summed up her findings: ‚ÄúOtherwise, no men of color, women of color or white women have held these positions. The franchise‚Äôs leading creative voices have been white men 96% of the time.‚Äù


For her findings, writers included anyone who received a screenplay or story credit on a Star Wars film. Ryan also included writers and directors who were fired from or left confirmed Star Wars projects, including Star Wars IX‚Äôs Colin Trevorrow as well as Solo‚Äôs Phil Lord and Chris Miller. However, Josh Trank, who was attached to direct a Star Wars standalone film before departing after the failure of his Fantastic Four, is not included in Ryan‚Äôs breakdown (though, if he were included, the percent calculated by Ryan wouldn‚Äôt change). The breakdown also only includes feature films, and doesn‚Äôt include those who have worked on Star Wars TV series like Star Wars: The Clone Wars and Star Wars Rebels.

To be clear, this breakdown of representation only looks at those who are writing and directing Star Wars movies; Ryan made note that the Star Wars movies released since 2012 have made strides in terms of more diverse casts and characters. However, movie writers and directors are undoubtedly the most important roles in terms of shaping and bringing these stories to life. And the call for more diversity in these creative roles extends beyond the galaxy far, far away.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
I understand that everyone is getting angry over the fact that the Jaegers are faster and sleeker in this version, but it actually kind of makes sense. 

Uprising takes place, in Del Toro's words when he was still working on the project, "A few years after the first one". A few years could range from anywhere from 5 years to 15 years. Let's say it takes place 5 years ahead of the first one just in case. This amount of time allows for multitudes of upgrades to be made to the Jaeger design, and of course, the countries would continue to make them (because they would either be 1. Skeptical of a secondary alien invasion or 2. Skeptical of other countries abusing this mechanical power as a militaristic strength). When so many engineers and scientists are focussing on one thing at any given time, a LOT usually gets done. This means that the research and development could have skyrocketed without the impending Kaiju invasion. This explains why the Jaegers could be so sleek and faster. 

I know everyone's getting pissed off about it, but I mean we're all really here to see massive robots v kaiju action here, so I still have hope for it (even if it's just a little bit).

Alright I noticed that people are thinking Transformers when they see this. Let me explain.

The Purpose of the Pan Pacific Defense Core was not only defeat Kaiju threats but also use as a way to share their technology with other countries in creating better Jagers without leaking top secret schematics. The Mark V Striker Eureka was the fastest one ever built, and it was essential to make faster Jagers since Catagory 4 Kaiju were smarter. In order to do so the builders found ways to make them slimmer and taller along with recreating the Drift System to help with reaction time.

For reference I look through the Universal Century of Gundam. That spanned Through 14 years where the Earth Federation and Zeon kept sending more Advanced Machines to battle another just as Advanced Machines. Pacific Rim Still is more relatable to Japanese Mecha Anime than Transformers.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
I loved the first one and the tone of this seems so different. It's just a trailer so maybe the final product will be different but it felt like robots were moving too fast and were to agile which were always one of the issues I had with the transformers movies. One of the things I loved about the first movie was that it felt like the Jaegers and Kaiju had real weight behind them. They were big massive tanks, not robot ninjas jumping around. 

Another thing is how bright everything is shot here, it felt more epic with all the major fights being at night since it made the colors of the cities, the Jaegers and the Kaijus being sliced and hit really stand out. Set the clips in the trailer at night and they would look way more epic. 

And of course the music choice for this was fucking awful. The trailer for the original had this awesome dark rock guitar that fit the theme perfectly, this is just generic Hip Hop. 

If this is survival, as the trailer says, then I don't think I want them to survive.

Comment:
The first one was good because it was over the top, didn't take itself seriously and had the feel of a classic cheesy monster movie. That was what made it fantastic.

Now we've got a movie that looks like it's going to take itself seriously and have none of Guillermo's passion or quirkiness. 

And I still don't buy that Stacker had a son we never heard of. I hate it when they do that shit. Not once did he ever mention having a son (even when Herc was talking about how Stacker was taking 'his son'). He didn't say "I know. I have a son too." It was always implied that Mako was his only family, even if she was 'adopted'. Mako also never mentions having a brother/adopted brother.

So that's going to be cringy in and of itself.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
Sad how the 'hip' thing is 'OMG it's not Directed by Del Toro it's just Transformers'....it is almost like nobody actually saw the first film. It was absolutely a cut above the average Transformers-type of blockbuster, but it was far from some flawless masterpiece.

The character archetypes used in the film were very pure and simple, they were all drawn in pretty one-note fashion. They've talked about how they are going for more complexity in the characters in this film.

Charlie Hunnam lacks charisma as a lead, ask the King Arthur movie. John Boyega has a lot more on-screen charisma.

The first film had pacing issues, and a middle chunk(Before the battle of Hong Kong) that takes too long to get going. It needed to be leaned out in the editing room. The Director is shooting for 2 hours with this film.

The first film shrouded all of its action scenes in rain, water, and night time. Interesting aesthetic choice, but fight scenes in broad daylight allow the fan to appreciate them in all of their glory.

The Director has stated his influences included Ultraman and Godzilla, which were among influences for Del Toro. They built off the Story Bible Del Toro developed on the first film. The notion of a Kaiju-Jaeger Hybrid? The concept of someone betraying humanity? Those are both ideas that Del Toro mentioned back in the early development of the sequel.

This movie is cut from the same cloth as the first film and honestly feels like a natural extension and evolution of that world. Only we're going to get a more charismatic lead, more interesting characters, and a better paced film. It's going to surprise everyone by being an improvement over the first film.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
I have some concerns

1. The movements of the jaegers- They just look too fast. I've been reading the comments and seeing people complain about the movements being to fast and people defending it saying "Its set further in the future so of course they'd be faster". The complaint about movement speed is stemming from the fact that because of how slow the movements were in the first movie it gave a feeling of weight and power to the jaegers, combined with the sounds it really felt like a 300 ton punching machine. Along with that I'd describe the fighting style of each movie as a heavy weight boxing/wrestling match for the first movie and ninja like fighting for uprising. I'm not entirely opposed to the fast movement decision if it was limited to 1/3 to 1/2 the jaegers, not most if not all judging by the trailer.

2.The jaeger design- This isn't as big of a problem but I'm not optimistic about most of the designs. Most of the jaegers seem to be going for the striker/typhoon slim design(though I'd say S/T did it better). It just seems to take away from the power of the jaegers making them seem like less of a giant machine and more(as people in the comments have already pointed out) seem more like transformers or power rangers. I do however like the look of(forgive me for not knowing his actual name) mace fist.

3. The characters- With the exception of John Boyegas character, the new characters look like they're going to be susceptible to the media trend of adding strong young/minority/female characters only to completely miss the mark and make them feel forced, lazily written and instead of being a strong character coming off as bitchy and unlikable(take Sarah Palmer from halo 4-5 as an example). 

I love the first movie and yes, i know this is just a trailer and I'm desperately hoping its good, but the fact that its not being directed by Guillermo Del Toro is the main thing giving me concerns about this movie. The man knew what made his movie great and without his mind behind this, it is very hard to put faith in this sequel.

The thing I didn‚Äôt like about the first one wasn‚Äôt that the story was lackluster or anything (what fucking dickhead went into a movie about giant mechs punching giant monsters expecting a good story), it was that there wasn‚Äôt enough action in it, and the lead guy wasn‚Äôt charismatic enough to make the bridges to the action fun enough. The movie had stretches where the action was abscent in favor of these stories that honestly came second to the main pull of these films, making me feel like a 10 year old again. Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
A handsome man went into a hotel and asked to see the boss. When the boss came, the story began.

-The client: is room 39 empty?
-The boss: yes, sir.
-The client: can I book it?
-The boss: of course you can.
-The client: thank you.

Before going to the room, the client asked the boss to provide him with a black knife, a white thread 39 cm and an orange 73g.

The boss agreed though he was surprized at the weird things the client asked to have.

The client went into his room, he didn't ask for food or anything else.

Unfortunately for the boss, his room was next to room 39.

After midnight, the boss heard strange voices and noise in that client's room. Voices of wild animals and of utensils and dishes being thrown on the floor.

The boss didn't sleep that night. He kept thinking and wondering what might be the source of the noise.

In the morning, when the client handed the keys to the boss, the latter asked to see the room first.

He went to the room and found everything alright. Nothing unusual. He even found the thread, the black knife and the orange on the table.

The client paid the bill and gave the bellboys a very good tip and left the hotel smiling.

The boss was in a shock but he didn't reveal what he heard to the bellboys. In fact, he started to doubt himself.

After one year, the client showed up again. He asked to see the boss again. The boss was in a puzzle.

The client asked the same things: room 39, black knife, white thread 39cm and an orange 79g.

This time, the boss wanted to know the truth by all means possible. He spent a sleepless night, waiting for something to happen. After midnight, the same voices and noises started, this time louder and more indecipherable than the year before.

Again, before leaving, the client paid his bill and left a large tip on the table for the bellboys. The smile didn't leave his face.

The boss started searching for the meaning of everything the client asked to have. Why did he ask room 39? why the white thread? why the black knife??? In fact, the boss didn't arrive to any convincing answer to all these questions.

The boss now was eagerly waiting for the month of March, the month in which the client showed up. 

To his surprise, on the first day of March, the same client showed up. He asked the same questions. Wanted to book the same room, wanted to have the same things as before.

The boss again heard the same noises, this time more louder than before.

In the morning, when the client was leaving the hotel, the boss apologized politely to the client and asked to know the secret behind the noises in the room.

-''If I tell you the secret, do you promise to never reveal it to anyone else?''
-''I promise I will never let anyone know''.
-''Swear''
-''I swear I won't reveal your secret''
So finally, the client revealed his secret to the boss. 

Unfortunately, the boss was a sincere person. Until now he hasn't revealed his secret to anyone.

When he does, I will let you know... thank you for reading.

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment: I am not appreciating the complete 180 in ary direction here. The first movie had bright and contrasting colors, sure, but it still felt gritty and heavy-toned. This is bright and colorful as hell, it seems comical almost. And the way they animate the Jaegers and Kaijus is different too. Its more fluid, more human, most importantly, its too fast. The way the first movie animated it was perfect. Jaegers were slow, hulking masses of towering metal, you could feel the weight of every step it took, every impact it made. The Kaijus were the same as well, flesh bobbed to and fro as they moved, giving the feeling that they truly are hulking masses of flesh and bone. Honestly, judging from the trailers, I might pass. I still want this movie to be successful though, maybe we can get a third one directed by Guillermo and its actually done right :/

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment: This only cements my fears. They've taken away what made the fights awesome in the original: the weight and scale. When Jeagers moved in the original, they didn't run, jump, and flip all over the place, they had to build up to that, because they were giant mechas. The weight behind their attacks made them feel way more satisfying to watch. The scaling also helped make the both the Jeagers and Kaiju seem huge and intimidating, making everything and everyone around them seem tiny and insignificant in comparison. And I know there's people out there who make the excuse that "these are more advanced Jeagers.", yeah, but they're still giant mechas, they shouldn't be doing a lot of the stuff seen here. By removing all of this they're making it look like a Bayformers movie. The Megazord in Power Rangers had more weight and somewhat better scaling.

Comment:
Well, where to start? I didn't really like the music, but that's just personal taste, so YMMV. 

The constant trailer cuts are obnoxious, but that's not a new thing.

The slow motion stuff looks pretty stupid, I really hope they don't use it much, because that's a cliche that can just go away. 

Kidvangelion? Please, no. When did this 'young adults in everything' trend start, the Hunger Games? It irks me, but if the script does it right, and the actors do a decent job, then it's fine. But that's kind of a lot of *if* there. 

All the weird weapons and new controls? We'll see. Again, it depends on if it's done well, or just shat all over the film. 

Now, the EXTREEEEEME Jager jumping, leaping, and sliding? Please, God, no, why? WHY are giant robots weighing tonnes in the four digit range running around like this is Tron 2? 

And lastly, lets get to possibly the biggest issue: WHY on EARTH is someone from Earth trying to bring *world-destroying monsters back*?! If this isn't turning out that Newt turned traitor because of being brainwashed over time when he drifted with that brain in the first movie, it's going to be so very, *very* stupid.

It was delayed, slow, never failing to remind viewers that these..things we're watching are mechs that weigh hundreds of tons. Comment:
Lol I see a lot of comments saying that this movie lacks realism just because the jaegers are lightweight and can do backflips. The thing is, the majority of action-packed movie-goers do not expect realism in movies, especially a movie that involves giant robots and monsters. So when the producers think about this majority, it simply means more profit. If they make the movie too realistic, I believe not many people are gonna watch it, thus less profit. For the first movie, I heard many people didn't like the night battle, which is why they make the sequel with daylight battle. 

Personally, I like the first one. And I know the sequel is gonna be good. Not great though. I don't mind if the jaegers manage to backflip, although I kinda agree that it defies physics. But who cares? As long as there are giant robots in action, I'm in. 

Also, I think that most people who condemn this movie are actually gonna watch it, probably to condemn it more, which is kinda stupid. Lol.

Looks like a bit of fun but doesn't have the same feel the first gave me to be honest. And it kind of feels like it undermines one of the major themes of the first film. While still being a Saturday morning cartoon of a film the first film still had a major theme of human beings uniting for once and being able to beat back a seemingly invincible foe because of it. But I may be overthinking a concept about robots punching monsters. 

Also a side note, the mechs don't look like they have any weight to them, at all. 

But i guess we'll see how good it is when it comes out.

Cant wait to see it. It just pisses me off that nyctophiliac are bashing on the film, just because there are no dark tones like the first one.

Look, the dark tones in the first film served its purpose. Hope was nearly gone. It would make no sense to do that again, because that hope is reguvinated. And a prequel wouldve just been a rehash of the first film.

I just dont get what is so wrong about being able to see these damn mechs now? Can anyone *really* say they fully enjoyed the fights in the first film? The ones with all the rain and mist, and majority of the film taking place at night?

I also like the mechs here are faster. I never did understood that, something giant moving slow, instead of moving like a regular person would. The Zord fight in Power Rangers 2017 had that problem too, hopefully that gets fixed in its sequel.

And when it comes to the new characters, one of the old characters from the first film is here too. So, Im sure we'll see Gypsy Danger fight(but I hope they dont kill the two off).

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
I wasn‚Äôt too sure about this after I watched the first time, but after watching again I think they have some pretty cool ideas. In Voltron and Power Rangers the mechs combine into one giant robot to fight the bad guys, but it looks like they turned that on its head and are making the kaiju ‚Äúmorph‚Äù together into one bigger enemy. The white mechs that open the breach have 3 fingers, it appears, and look very alien. Are they somehow controlled by the kaiju masters? Who on earth would strike a deal with them, and why? I like that the jaegers are still very different from each other, as in the first film it was stated that the kaiju were ‚Äúadapting‚Äù to human jaeger tactics. The young pilots seem odd at first, but I would have made a way better pilot at 17 than at 30, so maybe it‚Äôs not that weird. The kids in Ender‚Äôs Game (the book) accomplished feats adults couldn‚Äôt because their minds hadn‚Äôt been put into boxes yet. I buy that.

Honestly this trailer doesn‚Äôt look great, but that‚Äôs what I thought when I saw the trailer for the first film, as well. I only gave it a chance because Del Toro‚Äôs name was on it. I strapped myself in for a terrible action movie. But after that first fight, where Beckett has to watch his brother get ripped out of the cockpit, then gets his jaeger torn apart, I realized I was actually watching a good movie, and changed my attitude. It was cheesy, silly, full of one-liners, fake action and plot holes, but it was a GOOD MOVIE.

This trailer looks bad, but so did the trailers for the originals. I‚Äôm still going to see it and I hope I‚Äôll be as surprised as I was the first time.

Comment: I've read through the comment section, and agree with a lot of you. I'll add my 2 cents though. What was awesome about the fights in the 1st movie was that you got the emotional impact of the fight, you felt some level of connection with each Yaeger's pilots, and when each one went down swinging, it brought a tear to my eye. The orchestral score was rhythmic and mechanical to match the mechanical nature of the Yaeger's. Now we have big Power Rangers basically. They fly, they transform, they fight in packs, they all have bright colors so you can tell which is which. Add in the teenager lead roles, and it's further proof this was a sequel that no one expected, and few people now want. If you want a great "kids save the day" film, watch Ender's Game!

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
After the first trailer, I was extremely hesitant. Uprising just didn't seem to capture the spirit of the original. The Jaegers and Kaijus didn't look as real, there didn't seem to be as much lovely attention to detail that made them feel so... yeah, so real in the original. But now, I'm more hopeful. They did look pretty solid in some shots, and while little was given away about the story, it looks promising. Despite definitely being a different movie, you can now see more clearly that this is, like the original, a character-driven story. So... I don't know. Maybe this will still be good after all. I hope so. I'd scream if the sequel to my favourite movie of all time sucked! Why did you have to leave, delToro? Why? At least delToro was still a co-writer of the script, so it'll hopefully be good.

That said... please keep the music of the original! Pleasepleaseplease! I know it's a different composer, and of course he can do his own interpretation, but there just has to be at least one scene, preferably a drop scene, with the full, barely changed main theme from Ramin Djawadi!

I'm extremely hyped and extremely terrified at the same time. Please let this movie be good...

Title: Pacific Rim Uprising - Official Trailer 2 [HD]
Comment:
Ok,so let's break down everything wrong with this trailer.

1. Feeling of weight. Now pardon me if I sound like a billion other people when saying this,but unfortunately it is quite a prevalent issue,HOW IN THE FLYING FUCK ARE THE JAEGERS MOVING AROUND LIKE THAT?! It looks as if they're hollow cardboard cut-outs in terms of weight. I don't care if this is sci-fi,you have to at least TRY to have a hint of realism in there,otherwise you break the suspension of disbelief. And quite frankly,a 7000 ton,250 foot tall robot wouldn't be able to do half this stuff without collapsing under it's own weight. This looks like a freaking video game.

2. The setting. In the first movie you were always in the dark and the rain. The only true daylight scenes are in the beginning and the end of the movie. This is supposed to convey humanity's downward spiral towards the later half of the war,the twilight before the destruction of everything. The beginning is bright to signify humanity uniting and temporarily winning against the threat and the end...well ends with a sunrise to signify the beginning of a new era of peace. In this one it looks like a Michael Bay movie. No drama,no suspense,nothing,just bright sunny days to emphasize...idk. Also,in the first the darkness served a practical purpose as well,disguising some of CGI. Now don't get me wrong,the CGI is amazing,but inevitably there are going to be parts that look crappier that others. But that's the good thing about the darkness,that it hides these below average effects and let's you fully enjoy a scene without breaking the immersion. In this one...I refer back to my video game point.

3. The designs of the Jaegers themselves. These are incredibly generic designs for mechas. Aside from Gipsy Avenger,who's already ripping off two existing designs,namely the OG Gipsy and Striker Eureka,none of them stand out. In the first one,each Jaeger had a unique design which told exactly who they were and what fuction they played. Cherno's the tough bruiser,Crimson's the nimble fighter,Gipsy is the heroic brawler and Striker's the futuristic one. Now,all of them are the Striker Eureka archetype,except this time it's uninspired and old.

And finally,this might be just a problem with the trailer but still:
4.The music. In the first you had booming orchestral themes evoking the epicness of the situation and a sense of grandeur. Here,you have a shitty ass pop song that sounds like a million others meant to just appeal to the kiddies that wanna be "lit" and "cool".

It's pathetic how much of a sellout this feels. Pacific Rim seems to be another franchise that's succumbing to having it's soul sucked by the corporate executives. And I really,really hope I'm wrong about this and it turns out alright,but as it is now...Cthulhu help us.
